post_text:
UPDATE: Demolition of the former John Rogers Elementary School is scheduled to begin on Tuesday, September 15, 2020.

Voters authorized the demolition of the former school as part of the 2016 school bond. Demolition is necessary as the building cannot be occupied without costly repairs to meet building codes in areas such as fire safety, insulation, seismic, heating and air conditioning, lighting, and Americans with Disability Act requirements. Even then, it would be an inadequate education space due to the aging infrastructure.

Additional details linked below...

The annual OSD school year printed wall calendar will be given to each family at neighborhood schools as part of scheduled supply distributions. The 2020-21 calendar will also be posted on the school district website next week.

Families that do not pick up a copy as part of their school distribution may pick up a copy from 3-7 p.m. on Friday, September 18 at the Knox 111 Administrative Center. Calendars will be available on tables spaced for physical distancing outside of the front doors of the Administrative Center, located at 111 Bethel St. N.E., Olympia. OSD families may walk up or drive and park at the Administrative Center to pick up a calendar.

We have printed enough copies of the calendar to provide one copy per family. Thank you for your understanding! ğŸ“…ğŸ“ğŸ‘€ #OSDFriends #WallCalendars #ItsOfficial

Thank you to all of our OSD employees and community partners who contributed to this effort. We look forward to beginning our fall meal distribution program on the first day of school Wednesday, September 9.

Recently author/illustrator extraordinaire Darren Farrell stopped in for a Zoom meeting being hosted by our very own Garfield Elementary School First Grade Teacher, Mrs. Tanya Lee.

Mrs. Lee's son had a question about his book "Letter Town" so she contacted him to see about getting an answer. Darren immediately responded! Not only did he respond, but when he found out that Mrs. Lee was a first-grade teacher he offered to join in a Zoom meeting with her class and read some of his books and answer questions about his life as an author/illustrator. How cool is that?!?

This is a video of Darren reading his book 'Thank You, Octopus' to GES first grade students during their class Zoom meeting. Enjoy! ğŸ†ğŸ§¡ğŸ˜ğŸ–¤ğŸ“– #GarfieldES #AwesomeAuthorVisit #DarrenFarrell #WeLoveThankYouOctopus #ComeVisitUsForRealPostCOVID19

post_text:
With a heavy heart, we want to share with the community the sad news that Capital High School Interim Assistant Principal Gordon Chamberlain passed away yesterday, May 2.

Gordon is well known in the community, both as an educator in OSD for nearly 20 years and a keyboard player in the Mick Hart and the Classic Vinyl Band. He retired last June after working as a dean and teacher at Olympia High School and has also worked in various other leadership roles in the Olympia School District, including assistant principal/dean roles at Capital High School and Reeves Middle School.

Our thoughts go out to his family and many friends and colleagues. Olympia School District counselors and social workers are available to help with this loss. Please email the Communications department at communications@osd.wednet.edu. Your email will be directed to our Student Support team, and someone will connect with you.

We were thrilled to be invited into Jennifer Knight's 4th-grade classroom at Centennial Elementary School prior to the COVID-19 statewide shutdown.

On this particular day, Mrs. Knight's classroom had a special guest presenter, a professional stone carver from the Tenino area who brought in soapstone for the students and taught them how to carve, craft and work the stone.

Each student was given their own chunk of pe-shaped soapstone that they were instructed and encouraged to carve in whichever way they chose. It was amazing to see the looks of determination on the faces of students as they tackled this new skill. post_text:
What do you do once you finish putting together 70+ food and veggie bags for students? If you're our team of Garfield Elementary School paraeducators and teachers you dance!

Garfield ES hands out 140 or so bags every week with hand-written notes from staff included in each bag. These particular bags went to the Thurston County Food Bank FOREKids backpack program and were distributed specifically to GES students.

The FORKids Backpack program provides free weekend food bags to 2,000 kids in five local school districts, including 33 elementary schools and seven high schools. The program ensures that children who rely on free and reduced school lunch receive enough food for the weekend.

Work began today on a roundabout which will be located at the intersection of Henderson and Carlyon, directly in front of Pioneer Elementary School. Here are construction schedule details:

- Lane restrictions/alterations: April 16 (duration of 2-3 weeks)
- Additional traffic control signage: April 16
- Striping placement: April 16/17
- Saw cutting: April 17

Excavation work will not begin until concrete/asphalt product availability is secure. A Flagger will be deployed to the Henderson/Carlyon crosswalk during the noontime School Lunch Program. Social distancing by all employees has been emphasized and is in practice.

MEAL DISTRIBUTION UPDATE:
Weekend food packs will be available at all of our non-school distribution sites on Friday of each week.

Currently, the Food Bank is experiencing a lack of help because the majority of their volunteers have been asked to shelter in place. The Olympia School District Food Services Department has been asked by the Food Bank to help with the distribution of the weekend food packs that were normally distributed by Food Bank volunteers.

This week, Governor Inslee asked the National Guard to help by volunteering at Food Banks due to the lack of volunteers. This should help the Food Bank get the distribution of weekend food packs back on track.

With our schools closed, there were a number of supplies in our buildings that were of an immediate need to first responders. Our Executive Director of Operations, Frank Wilson, gathered these items up and donated them to Thurston County Medic One. These items were collected from our school emergency bags/bins, health rooms as well as items we had ordered to prepare for school during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The donated items will be distributed throughout the medical community and to first responders in Thurston County. These items will be replenished for our buildings as soon as stock is made available. Thank you to all our first responders! ğŸ’¯â¤ï¸ğŸ’¯ #OSDFriends #EveryLittleBitCounts #FirstResponders

Here is a list of the donated supplies:

Nitrile Gloves - 4,200
Vinyl Gloves - 2,000
Mask (Surgical) - 900
Mask (Particulate) - 581
Mask (N95) - 200
Safety Glasses - 97
Respirators - 40
Hand Sanitizer - 2

Late this afternoon, Gov. Jay Inslee ordered Washingtonians to â€œStay Home, Stay Healthyâ€ for a minimum of two weeks as the state tries to slow the growing spread of COVID-19. Gov. Inslee ordered all Washington residents to stay at home except for crucial activities like buying groceries, seeking medical care or going to work at essential businesses.

While he also encouraged people to continue to exercise, including walking, biking or gardening, he cautioned against participating in any activities that are contrary to social distancing directives.

Given this new order, effective tomorrow, Tuesday, March 24, we will close all OSD outdoor facilities, including fields, tracks, tennis courts, batting cages, playgrounds and other areas, to the public.

Read the full statement below...

post_text:
DISTRICT OFFICE CLOSURE
In line with the social distancing directives from both Gov. Jay Inslee and federal health officials, the Knox 111 Administrative Center will close to the public for two weeks, effective tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17. The District Office will remain closed through Tuesday, March 31, or until further notice.

For now, plans are to reopen the district office on Wednesday, April 1. While the district office is closed, we will continue to check messages to the main receptionist phone (360) 596-6100, as well as emails sent to communications@osd.wednet.edu. Thank you.

For now, plans are to reopen the district office on Wednesday, April 1. While the district office is closed, we will continue to check messages to the main receptionist phone (360) 596-6100, as well as emails sent to communications@osd.wednet.edu. Thank you.

We learned tonight that false information about our district related to coronavirus (COVID-19) has been shared on a mobile messaging application. It was reported to us that the false information was shared on Snapchat, including an altered photo of one of our school websites. The message states that OSD schools will be closed next week for sanitation purposes. This is NOT true.

As always, in the event of a school closure or other school schedule change, we will communicate directly to families and staff through our automated communication system. This includes an email, text and RoboCall sent by OSD Communications. We will also post school schedule information as a drop-down alert on our website and post on our official OSD social media platforms. ğŸ‘ˆğŸ¼ğŸ‘€ ğŸ“Œ#OSDFriends #FalseInfo #CheckOurFeedFirst

post_text:
ğŸŸğŸ¨ğŸŒ "At the beginning of the year, I ask our families what they could bring to enrich our learning. It's added so many dimensions to teaching and learning in my room," says Elizabeth Wilson, a second grade teacher at Boston Harbor ES. Troy Beedle, a BHES parent and member of the Skokomish tribe, brought in chum salmon that he'd caught. The students painted the salmon with black paint and then used that platform to create a fish impression on a large piece of paper. Beedle talked with the students about fishing and what they liked to catch. Nora Gant and Jean Gant Delestrada also helped with the salmon press. The students were thrilled to have them there. Thank you to our wonderful volunteers! #CulturalOpportunities #AwesomeVolunteers #SalmonArt

shared_text:
Olympia High School
February 5 at 4:34 PM Â·

This week is National School Counseling week! We have amazing Counselors here at OHS and we want to take the time to recognize each one of them this week.

Next in line is Derek Bonaldo. Derek counsels students Hj-Mc. Derek joined us this year after interning at Steilacoom High School. He is in his second year of being a School Counselor.

Derek has been married for 16 years, loves dogs, and is a Retired Army Officer with 23 years of service.

His favorite thing about being at OHS? The awesome staff of course! Real pleasure to work with and all are very helpful to a rookie like me!

We all know, it can be hard coming into a new place, but Mr. Bonaldo, we have your back like you do for our students! Thank you and welcome to the FamOly!

post_text:
Update: 11:59 a.m. Jan. 17
Students throughout the district will be dropped off this afternoon on regular bus routes.

Due to icy roads, all OSD schools will start two hours late today, Friday, January 17. Buses will also pick up students two hours late this morning. Buses will pick up students this morning on regular routes except for Routes 64 (Summit Lake) and Routes 50 (Cedar Flats), which are on snow routes. There is no out-of-district transportation.

There is no AM preschool, no zero hour classes, no before-school activities, and no Avanti HS AM tutoring or academic services. Breakfast and lunch will be served throughout the district.

Due to icy roads, all Olympia School District schools will start two hours late today, Tuesday, January 14. Buses will also pick up children two hours late this morning and will run on snow routes. There is no out-of-district transportation.

There is no a.m. preschool, no zero hour classes, no before-school activities such as music or clubs, and no a.m. Avanti High School program (for periods 1-3). Breakfast and lunch will be served throughout the district.

The Olympia School Board has unanimously agreed to place an Educational Programs and Operations Replacement Levy proposal before voters on the February 11, 2020 Special Election ballot.

The proposed levy is not a new tax. The measure on the February 2020 ballot would replace an expiring four-year educational programs levy approved by voters in February 2016.

School levies are the only locally approved ballot measures that directly pay for classroom and educational needs of students not funded by the state.ğŸ’›ğŸ’“ğŸ’™ #OSDFriends #SpecialElection #OlyLove
